"title": "5950: silence",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5950",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A stillness or absence of noise, often associated with the absence of life or people, but also associated with a sense of expectancy or reverence, especially in the presence of God. Scripture stresses that God is not silent, but has spoken his word to his creation. The silence of Jesus Christ before his accusers is seen as the fulfilment of OT prophecy.</p>\n<h2>The silence of God</h2>\n<h3>His apparent silence in the face of sin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps50:21\">PSA 50:21</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job34:29\">JOB 34:29</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa42:14\">ISA 42:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa57:11\">ISA 57:11</a></p>\n<h3>God will not remain silent in the face of sin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps50:3\">PSA 50:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:1\">ISA 62:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa65:6-Isa65:7\">ISA 65:6–65:7</a></p>\n<h3>Prayers that God will not be silent</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps28:1\">PSA 28:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps35:22\">PSA 35:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:12\">PSA 39:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps83:1\">PSA 83:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps109:1\">PSA 109:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa64:12\">ISA 64:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hab1:13\">HAB 1:13</a></p>\n<h2>God silences those who oppose him</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:9\">1SA 2:9</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps8:2\">PSA 8:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps63:11\">PSA 63:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:42\">PSA 107:42</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa25:5\">ISA 25:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa47:5\">ISA 47:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer47:5\">JER 47:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer48:2\">JER 48:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer51:55\">JER 51:55</a>MAT <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer22:34\">22:34</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark3:4\">MRK 3:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke20:26\">LUK 20:26</a>\n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:14\">ACT 4:14</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom3:19\">ROM 3:19</a></p>\n<h2>The silence of Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>It was foretold in the OT</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa53:7\">ISA 53:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:32\">ACT 8:32</a></p>\n<h3>Its fulfilment in the NT</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:63\">MAT 26:63</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:61\">MRK 14:61</a> <em>before the Sanhedrin</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt27:14\">MAT 27:14</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark15:4-Mark15:5\">MRK 15:4–15:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:9\">JHN 19:9</a> <em>before Pilate</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:9\">LUK 23:9</a> <em>before Herod</em></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ commands silence as a sign of his authority</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:25-Mark1:26\">MRK 1:25–1:26</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:35\">LUK 4:35</a> <em>Jesus Christ silenced evil spirits</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark4:39\">MRK 4:39</a> <em>Jesus Christ silenced the storm.</em></p>\n<h2>There are times when it is appropriate for God's people to be silent</h2>\n<h3>The silence of expecting God to act</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh6:10\">JOS 6:10</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen24:21\">GEN 24:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod14:14-Exod14:15\">EXO 14:14–14:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs2:3\">2KI 2:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs2:5\">2KI 2:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev8:1\">REV 8:1</a></p>\n<h3>The silence anticipating the wisdom of another person</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job29:7-Job29:10\">JOB 29:7–29:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job29:21\">JOB 29:21</a></p>\n<h3>The silence of prudence</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov10:19\">PRO 10:19</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl3:7\">ECC 3:7</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam10:27\">1SA 10:27</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job13:5\">JOB 13:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job33:31-Job33:33\">JOB 33:31–33:33</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov11:12\">PRO 11:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov17:28\">PRO 17:28</a></p>\n<h3>The silence of suffering</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam3:28\">LAM 3:28</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:9\">PSA 39:9</a></p>\n<h3>The silence of shame</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek16:63\">EZK 16:63</a></p>\n<h3>The silence of anger</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps4:4\">PSA 4:4</a></strong> <em>The psalmist is warning against hasty action when angry.</em></p>\n<h3>The silence of amazement at God's actions</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke9:36\">LUK 9:36</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:12\">ACT 15:12</a></p>\n<h3>A tongues-speaker should be silent if no interpreter is present</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor14:28\">1CO 14:28</a> <em>silence in the church</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor14:30\">1CO 14:30</a> <em>A prophet should be silent if another receives a revelation.</em></p>\n<h3>Christian women are sometimes exorted to be silent</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Tim2:11-1Tim2:12\">1TI 2:11–2:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor14:34-1Cor14:35\">1CO 14:34–14:35</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet3:1-1Pet3:4\">1PE 3:1–3:4</a></p>\n<h2>There are times when it is inappropriate for God's people to be silent</h2>\n<h3>When there is good news to tell</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:9\">2KI 7:9</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps40:9\">PSA 40:9</a></p>\n<h3>When much depends upon a person's words</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth4:14\">EST 4:14</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer4:19\">JER 4:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer20:9\">JER 20:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:9-Acts18:10\">ACT 18:9–18:10</a></p>\n<h3>When God should be praised</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps30:11-Ps30:12\">PSA 30:11–30:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke19:37-Luke19:40\">LUK 19:37–19:40</a></p>\n<h3>When sin is unconfessed</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps32:3\">PSA 32:3</a></strong></p>\n<h3>When God's people feel they have a genuine complaint</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps39:1-Ps39:2\">PSA 39:1–39:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job7:11\">JOB 7:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job23:16-Job23:17\">JOB 23:16–23:17</a></p>\n<h3>When prayer is urgently required</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa62:6-Isa62:7\">ISA 62:6–62:7</a></p>\n<h2>God's people are sometimes brought to silence</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job31:34\">JOB 31:34</a> <em>Job fearing the crowd</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek3:26\">EZK 3:26</a> <em>Ezekiel as a judgment on Israel</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark9:34\">MRK 9:34</a> <em>the disciples when their pride was exposed</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:20\">LUK 1:20</a> <em>Zechariah because of his unbelief</em></p>\n<h2>Silencing the wicked</h2>\n<h3>Believers pray that the wicked will be silenced</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps31:17-Ps31:18\">PSA 31:17–31:18</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet2:23\">1PE 2:23</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps143:12\">PSA 143:12</a></p>\n<h3>Believers so live that the wicked may be silenced</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus2:8\">TIT 2:8</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet2:15\">1PE 2:15</a></p>\n<h2>False teachers must be silenced</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Titus1:10-Titus1:11\">TIT 1:10–1:11</a></strong> <em>“the circumcision group” believed that in order to be saved it was necessary to be circumcised and keep the Jewish ceremonial law.</em></p>\n<h2>Death is compared to silence</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps94:17\">PSA 94:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps115:17\">PSA 115:17</a></p>",
